Sixty-two  strains showed antibacterial activity against A. tumefaciens,  Our  intensive  screening  resulted  in  finding  the  active  strain,  Streptomyces  sp.  TM-71.  This  strain  produced  julimycin  B-II  and julichrome  Q1.3'  both  showing  potent  inhibitory  activity  against  crown  gall  formation  without  affecting bacterial growth or alfalfa germination. This paper  describes  the  isolation  of these  two  plant  transformation  inhibitors.

In  the  course  of our  screening  for  inhibitors  of crown  gall  formation,  we  have  previously  isolated  oxazolomycin  from the culture broth of Streptomyces sp.  KBFP-2025 and  reported  that  the  inhibitory  activity  against  crown  gall  formation  was  due  to its  strong antibacterial effect  on the  pathogen,  A.  tumefaciens. 4 )  Cycloheximide,  a  phytotoxic  compound,  also  inhibited crown gall  formation  on potato  tuber  disks,  but  simultaneously  caused  necrosis.  These  results  showed  that the potato tuber disk  assay  entrapped  not  only  specific  crown  gall  formation  inhibitors  but also  antibacterial or phytotoxic compounds.  This led  us  to test  the  antibacterial  or  phytotoxic  activity  of  the  microbial  culture broth first,  and to screen only those broths without  antibacterial or phytotoxic activity for their ability to inhibit  crown  gall  formation  on  potato  tuber  disks.  Simple  antibacterial  and  phytotoxic  time  consuming  potato  tuber  disk  assay  excluded  the  culture  broths showing antibacterial or phytotoxic activity.  The  mechanism  of  plant  transformation  by  Agro  bacterium species has been studied in detail. 3) However, the  complete mechanism has not been elucidated. The discovery  of effective  chemical  probes  for  plant  transformation  is  useful for  studying the transformation mechanism.  Many  scientists'  attention  has  been  focused  on  a  plant  transformation  system  which  in  Agrobacterium  species  as  a  vector.  This  system  has  been  applied to the effective production of useful compounds as  well  as  to  the  creation of plants acquiring new characters.  Some  transgenic  plants,  e.g.,  herbicide-resistant  or  virus  resistant types,  have  already been generated. 1,2)  Bisanthraquinones,  Inhibitors  of Plant Transformation

A potato  tuber  disk  assay  of culture  broths  which  had  been  confirmed  to  show  neither  antibacterial  nor phytotoxic activity resulted in the discovery of a novel type of crown gall formation inhibitors, julimycin  B-II  and  julichrome  Q1.3'  These  two  bisanthraquinones,  products  of Streptomyces  sp.  TM-71,  inhibited  crown  gall formation  on  potato  tuber  disks  at a minimum  inhibitory  dose  of 1.6 JIg/disk  without  affecting  the  growth  of Agrobacterium tumefaciens or the  germination of alfalfa seeds.

Its  IR  spectrum  indicated  the  presence  of  hydroxyl  (3490 cm - 1),  ester  carbonyl  (1725 cm -1),  non-chelated  carbonyl  (1685 cm -1)  and  chelated  carbonyl  groups  (1650cm- 1).  A  IH-NMR  signal  at  J  12.94  in  CDCI3,  which  disappeared  with  the  addition of D20, showed the presence of an intramolecular  hydrogen-bonded  OH  group. The ethyl  acetate  fraction  was  chromatographed  twice  on  Sephadex  LH -20  to give  compounds 1 and 2.

The  remaining  138  strains  were  subjected to the potato tuber disk assay, which revealed  14  candidates  for  producers  of specific  plant  transformation  inhibitors.  The  active  strains  were  cultivated  again  under  the  same  conditions.  The  culture  broths  were  then  partitioned  with  ethyl  acetate  followed  by  n-BuOH.  The  water-soluble  fraction  was  lyophilized,  and then  extracted  with  acetone  and  subsequently  with  MeOH.  These  four  fractions of the 14 strains were applied to the antibacterial,  phytotoxic  and  potato  tuber  disk  assays  again  to  exclude  those  fractions  with  weak  antibacterial  or  phytotoxic  activity.  Among the fractions  tested,  only the ethyl acetate  fraction  of  Streptomyces  sp.  TM-71  showed  inhibitory  activity against crown gall formation, with neither inhibito  ry  activity  against  A.  tumefaciens  growth  nor  alfalfa  ger  mination,  even  at high  doses. These results indicated that 1  was  a  bisanthraquinone  with  a  center  of  symmetry.  A  complete  assignment  of the  IH-NMR  signals  of active  1  led us to identify 1 asjulimycin B-II Gulichrome Q1.I), which  has been isolated as  an antiviral antibiotic. 7

The  minimum  inhibitory  doses  of julimycin  B-II  and  julichrome  Q1.3  in  the  potato  tuber  disk  assay  were  both  1.6 ~g/disk.  These  compounds  neither  caused  necrosis  of  potato  tuber  disks,  even  at  a  dose  of  100 ~g/disk,  nor  inhibited the germination of alfalfa seeds, even at a dose of  50 ~g/disk. Neither 1 nor 2 showed any antibacterial activity  (minimum inhibitory concentration of > 500 ~g/ml) against  A.  tumefaciens, in striking contrast to oxazolomycin, which  had  selective  antibacterial  activity  against  A.  tumefaciens  (minimum  inhibitory  concentration  of 3.1 ~g/ml).4) These  data indicate  that these  two  active  compounds  specifically  inhibited any step of plant transformation without affecting  A.  tumefaciens  or  the  plant cells,  and  that  they  would  be  promising  as  chemical  probes  for  elucidating  the  plant  transformation mechanism. Effect  on  crown  gall  formation  of the  active  compounds  administered after  inoculating potato  tuber  disks  with  A.  tumefaciens  In the previous paper, 4)  we examined the effect on crown  gall  formation  of  the  active  compounds  administered  a  certain  time  after  inoculating  potato  disks  with  A.  tumefaciens.  Julichrome  Q1.3  did  not  inhibit  crown  gall  formation when administered 12 h or more after inoc-qlating  with  A.  tumefaciens  (Table).  No  phytotoxic  activity  was  observed  even  against  crown  gall  cells.  These  findings  indicated that the plant transformation of potato tuber cells  by  A.  tumefaciens might be completed within  12-24 h after  inoculating with the bacterium. This result is consistent with  our previous  studies  of oxazolomycin. 4 )  This  time  for  the  completion  of  plant  transformation  coincides  with  the  results  by  Stachel  et  al.  that  single-strand  T-DNA  was  detected in the cells of A. tumefaciens 8 h after the induction  of vir  genes  by acetosyringone,  and reached  the maximum  level  after  12 h. 10)

The  isolation  and  characterization  of  20  julichrome  derivatives from Streptomyces shiodaensis nov. sp. has been  reported  by  the  research  group  at  Shionogi  Research  Laboratory.6-9,1l  16)  In this paper, we  report that two of  these derivatives had unique inhibitory activity against plant  transformation.  It is  interesting  in  view  of the  structure  activity  relationship  to  measure  the  bioactive  spectra  of  other julichromes. Julimycin B-II has been reported to show  a  chemoprophylactic  effect  against  poliovirus  infection in  mice15) and  Friend virus  leukemia. 16) Both  the  poliovirus  and Friend virus are in the RNA virus category, and viruses  are thought to have  originated from  plasmids during their  evolution. I 7)  These  facts  suggest  that one  of the  steps  for  plant transformation by  A.  tumefaciens might be similar to  the step of RNA virus infection such as replication, transfer  to the host cells, or integration into the host chromosome.  Further,  Julimycin  B-II  had  antitumor  activity  against  HeLa cells, Ehlrich ascites carcinoma and ascites hepatoma  AH-130. 16) Ferrigni et al. IS ) have reported that data for the  potato tuber disk assay were positively associated with those  of the  in  vivo  mouse  leukemia assay.  These  results  suggest  that  crown  gall  formation  inhibitors  would  also  be  promising as antiviral or antitumor substances and be useful  to  study  the  mechanism  for  viral  infection  and  tumor  formation.  + +,  strong  inhibition;  +,  inhibition;  ±, weak  inhibition;  -, no  in  Bioassay system. Isolation  of active  compounds  1  and 2.  Strain  TM-71  was  reciprocally  subcultured in test tubes (ljJ = 25 mm,  10 ml)  at 27 DC for 4 days. Thirty-ml  portions  of the  subculture  were  each  transferred into  a  5-liter  mini-jar  fermentor  containing  3  liters  of the  medium  described  in  the  screening  section.  The fermentation was carried out at 27°C for  5 days  (aeration at  2.5  liters/min  and  agitation  of 400 rpm),  and  the  culture  broth  (6  liters)  was filtered. The culture filtrate (5.5 liters) was extracted with ethyl acetate.  The ethyl  acetate  fraction  was  concentrated  in  vacuo,  and  350mg of the  residue (1050 mg in  total) was  subjected to chromatography on Sephadex  LH-20(Pharmacia-LKB, Sweden, ljJ1.6 x 100cm), eluting with 40% MeOH  at a flow rate of 0:5 ml/min (10 mlper fraction). Fractions 47 to 67 (38.5 mg)  and  fractions  68  to  95  (27.5 mg)  were  separately  rechromatographed  on  ,Sephadex  LH~20 to  give  1 (17.2mg)' and 2 (5.6mg).

Sample preparation for screening. Actinomycetes isolated from soil were  grown  in  10ml of a potato-sucrose-malt extract medium with shaking at  27 DC  for  4  days.  The  lyophilized  culture  broth  was  then  extracted  with  10ml MeOH, the MeOH-soluble fraction being concentrated in  vacuo and  dissolved  in  1 ml  of  50%  MeOH.  This  solution  was  applied  to  the  antibacterial  (100 j.ll/paper disk)  and phytotoxic (20 ttl/paper disk)  assays  prior to  the potato tuber disk  assay  (25 ttl/potato tuber disk).  The active  strains from  the potato tuber disk  assay were  cultivated  again  under  the  same  conditions.  The  culture  broth  (10 ml)  was  partitioned  with  ethyl  acetate followed  by n-BuOH.  The water-soluble fraction  was  lyophilized,  and successively extracted with acetone and MeOH.  After concentration,  the ethyl acetate-seluble fraction was dissolved in  1 ml of MeOH, and the  other solvents'soluble fractions  in 1 ml  of 50%  MeOH. Analytical  methods.  IH-NMR  spectra  were  recorded  with  a  Varian  VXR -500 instrument and MS spectra were measured with a JEO L SX -1 02A  mas,s spectrometer. IR and UV spectra were obtained with Hitachi EPI-G3  and Shimadzu UV-300Q spectrophotometers, respectively. The purification  pr6cess  was  monitored  by  thin-layer  chromatognlphy  on  silica' gel  (E.  Merck;; Kiese1ge1  60  F 254'  Art.  5554)  using benzene-ethyl acetate-MeOH  (6: 3: 1)  as the  developing  solvent.  Phytotoxicity was determined by a germination test using alfalfa (M edicago  sativa) seeds on a paper disk (4)= 15mm) carrying a test material. MeOH  extracts oflyophilized culture broths were assayed for antibacterial activity  against A. tumefaciens by the paper-disk method. The minimum inhibitory  concentration  of  the  isolated  compounds  against  A.  tumefaciens  was  measured by  the  dilution method described previously.4)  Acknowledgments.
